
URL reference: https://linuxsecurity.com/features/linux-kernel-module-hardening-modulejail
DateReviewed: 2026-06-01
Description: Our article today will talk about Kernel modules which we aren't using and how that plays into security. The thing is that your system is very smart nowadays, and the core kernel is fairly tight, with a lot of optional pieces relegated to being loaded as needed as the kernel needs it as a module. This piece explains that things you aren't using and aren't normally loaded could be pulled in if things go the right way, and that could expose you to a security issue you might not normally consider. Our authors mention something called ModuleJail, which sees what you are currently using and builds a potential blacklist to reject if you don't need other kernel modules. They then talk about what these magic modules do - namely, talk to thinks like hardware drivers, network cards and features, filesystems and more. The idea here is you can load the module for your network card, not every network card that Linux supports. The idea they advance, which is sound, is that servers need some drivers, but a DB server doesn't need some esoterice FS drivers, and a web server won't need fancy video card support drivers. So the idea is to look at what you are using now, but also to look through recent boot logs and such to see historically what has been needed; build a whitelist of required modules, and then add other things to a potential blacklist, only enabling it after a good amount of testing.
BottomLine: Strong approach to the idea of restricting Linux kernel modules for security reasons
