Description: Today we'll dive into why many home lab Kubernetes setups fail. This is a blog, so we dive right in - our author has talked to some lab builders, and the story is the same - they take a weekend, build a cluster, watch some YT vids and deploy a sample app, and sometimes get ingress working. Then, they stop touching it. Clusters runs, but they aren't using it to learn. And he thinks he knows why this happens again and again. Traditional home labs focus on infra - what tools, what distros (K3s, Talos, etc). Experiment with network, storage, load balancers and GitOps tools. The issue, he points out, is that you still might not be able to deploy a service, fiddle with ingress, set up a persistent volume or many other things, including troubleshooting. He says that it's important to *use* K8s, not just spin up clusters. The idea is to try new things, use K8s, watch it break and then fix it. Adding ingress, fiddling with replica counts, seeing what happens when a pod crashes. The strong suggestiong is mindset approach - not "what cluster should I build", but "what concepts do I want to practice"? The author mentions and links to a K8s learning platform that helped them. I like this approach very much.
BottomLine: Good strategic appraoch to building a Kubernetes homelab
