URL reference: https://medium.com/airbnb-engineering/sitar-agent-building-a-reliable-dynamic-configuration-sidecar-at-scale-b7e00c152068
DateReviewed: 2026-06-16
Description: Our post today is a forray into a bit of Airbnb's infra, paticularly their dynamic config system. A previous post had talked about how a change to the system is built; this post looks at how it is enacted. It turns out they run an agent in a sidecar, which subscribes to changes and updates what is then the local filesystem with the new config. And with a nice diagram they go through the process, from a config change being done and then validated, to creation of an hourly snapshot, then having new pods pull the snapshot to establish a baseline, then asking the sitar service if there are any new changes. After startup, the sidecar polls the service for changes; the app reads the shared FS mount which has the latest up to date changes. One thing they point out - with this design, even if the main sitar service is down, pods can start based on the snapshot configs. They then go on to discuss the pros and cons of using the main container to manage configs versus using a sidecar. They even talk about the polling architecture, and optimizations they use which cut down on unneeded retrieval of configs. Finally they went through a migration on their data store, from an older tech to SQLite, while also comparing RocksDB as a contender. Very well written and worth reading.
BottomLine: Walkthrough of AirBNBs dynamic config update system
